      "message": "I guess why we got an ugly interface here is because I do not have a very clear way to tell if the incoming messages are drain without interrupting the render. In the current implementation, when messages are drain and a snapshot is requested, it unblocks the render thread and let it go into the snapshot code path. It requires a lot of coupling between a render thread and its render channel. An alternative would be instead of unblocking the render thread, we keep the render thread blocked and the snapshot thread saves the state of the render thread. The only trick is to figure out whether the render thread is blocked by read because we do not want those 2 threads to run in parallel. This should make a much cleaner interface. Does it sound better?\n\nThe current snapshot code path is pretty different from your proposed code path. The render thread snapshot is triggered by the OpenglEsPipe snapshot. The benefit is that it sets up all the pipe stuff and render threads for us. Snapshot loading is simple because it sets up render threads, and all render threads are blocked by read before restoration is done (because we snapshot them when they are blocked by read). It is pretty safe to restore whatever when they are blocked. The drawback is, as you can see, it is not very parallel unless we make the pipe snapshot parallel.",
